Wrangling Data II:
Working with Text

Strings

Strings are simply data in the form of characters rather than numbers. Still, they can be a bit trickier to deal with. The stringr package simplifies the process, and all of its commands begin with str_ to make them a bit easier to remember.

library(tidyverse)  # loads ggplot2, tibble, tidyr, readr,
                    # purrr, and dplyr
library(stringr)

String Basics

str_c() combines two or more strings. Use the sep argument to define how the combined strings will be separated.

days <- c("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday",
          "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday")
ordinals <- c("1st", "2nd", "3rd", "4th", "5th", "6th", "7th")

str_c(days, ", January ", ordinals, ", 2017")
## [1] "Sunday, January 1st, 2017"   
## [2] "Monday, January 2nd, 2017"   
## [3] "Tuesday, January 3rd, 2017"  
## [4] "Wednesday, January 4th, 2017"
## [5] "Thursday, January 5th, 2017" 
## [6] "Friday, January 6th, 2017"   
## [7] "Saturday, January 7th, 2017"

String Basics

str_c() combines two or more strings. Use the sep argument to define how the combined strings will be separated.

Use the collapse argument to combine the elements of a vector into a single string.

str_c(days, collapse = "|")
## [1] "Sunday|Monday|Tuesday|Wednesday|Thursday|Friday|Saturday"

String Basics

str_sub() subsets a string: you tell it where to start and stop.

str_sub(days, start = 1, end = 1)
## [1] "S" "M" "T" "W" "T" "F" "S"

String Basics

str_sub() subsets a string: you tell it where to start and stop. Use negative numbers to count from the end of the string.

str_sub(days, start = -1, end = -1) 
## [1] "y" "y" "y" "y" "y" "y" "y"
# Oh, good!

Using Regular Expressions in R

  • str_detect(): Does the regex pattern appear?
  • str_extract() and str_extract_all(): Get the pattern
  • str_replace() and str_replace_all(): Swap out the pattern
  • tidyr::separate(): Break up the variable at the pattern

Regular Expressions

  • Every character matches itself

Regular Expressions

  • Every character matches itself
str_detect(days, "T")
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE

Regular Expressions

  • Every character matches itself
str_detect(days, "T") %>% which()
## [1] 3 5

Regular Expressions: Basics

  • Every character matches itself
str_detect(days, "T") %>% which()
## [1] 3 5
str_detect(days, "Th") %>% which()
## [1] 5

Regular Expressions: Basics

  • . : Any character (including spaces, etc.)
str_extract(days, ".")
## [1] "S" "M" "T" "W" "T" "F" "S"

Regular Expressions: Repetition

  • * and + : Greedy repetition (0 or more and 1 or more)
str_extract(days, ".*")
## [1] "Sunday"    "Monday"    "Tuesday"   "Wednesday"
## [5] "Thursday"  "Friday"    "Saturday"

Regular Expressions: Repetition

  • {2} : Fixed repetition, in this case 2 times
str_extract(days, ".{2}")
## [1] "Su" "Mo" "Tu" "We" "Th" "Fr" "Sa"

Regular Expressions: Repetition

  • {7,} : At least repetition; here, at least 7 times
str_extract(days, ".{7,}")
## [1] NA          NA          "Tuesday"   "Wednesday"
## [5] "Thursday"  NA          "Saturday"

Regular Expressions: Repetition

  • {7,} : At least repetition; here, at least 7 times
str_extract(days, ".{7,}")
## [1] NA          NA          "Tuesday"   "Wednesday"
## [5] "Thursday"  NA          "Saturday"
str_extract(days, ".{7,}") %>% str_length()
## [1] NA NA  7  9  8 NA  8

Regular Expressions: Repetition

  • {7,8} : Between repetition; here, at least 7 times but not more than 8
str_extract(days, ".{7,8}")
## [1] NA         NA         "Tuesday"  "Wednesda" "Thursday"
## [6] NA         "Saturday"
str_extract(days, ".{7,8}") %>% str_length()
## [1] NA NA  7  8  8 NA  8

Regular Expressions: Optional Matches

  • ? : Greedy optional match (match 0 or 1 times, prefer 1)
str_extract(days, ".at")
## [1] NA    NA    NA    NA    NA    NA    "Sat"
str_extract(days, ".at?")
## [1] "da"  "da"  "da"  "da"  "da"  "da"  "Sat"

Regular Expressions: Optional Matches

  • ?? : Lazy optional match (match 0 or 1 times, prefer 0)
str_extract_all(days, ".at?") %>% unlist() # unlist() just to fit slide
## [1] "da"  "da"  "da"  "da"  "da"  "da"  "Sat" "da"
str_extract_all(days, ".at??") %>% unlist() 
## [1] "da" "da" "da" "da" "da" "da" "Sa" "da"

Regular Expressions: Repetition

  • *? and +? : Lazy repetition (0 or more and 1 or more)
str_extract(days, "a.+")
## [1] "ay"      "ay"      "ay"      "ay"      "ay"     
## [6] "ay"      "aturday"
str_extract(days, "a.+?")
## [1] "ay" "ay" "ay" "ay" "ay" "ay" "at"

Regular Expressions: Anchors

  • ^ and $ : The beginning and end of the string
str_extract(days, ".a.")
## [1] "day" "day" "day" "day" "day" "day" "Sat"
str_extract(days, "^.a.")
## [1] NA    NA    NA    NA    NA    NA    "Sat"
str_extract(days, ".a.$")
## [1] "day" "day" "day" "day" "day" "day" "day"

Regular Expressions: Character Classes

  • Make your own wildcard with [ and ]!
str_extract(days, ".[aeiou]") # any character & then a lowercase vowel
## [1] "Su" "Mo" "Tu" "We" "hu" "ri" "Sa"

Regular Expressions: Character Classes

  • Within a character class, ^ means not
str_extract(days, ".[^aeiou]") # any character & then one NOT a lc vowel
## [1] "un" "on" "es" "ed" "Th" "Fr" "at"

Regular Expressions: Character Classes

str_extract(c("hi", "324"), "\\d+") # \\d: digit
## [1] NA    "324"
str_extract(days, "\\D") # \\D: not a digit
## [1] "S" "M" "T" "W" "T" "F" "S"
# \\w: 'word' [A-Za-z0-9_]; \\W: not word
str_detect(c("123", "abc", ", "), "\\W") 
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE

Regular Expressions: Character Classes

# \\b: boundary
str_detect(c("dog", "dog is good", 
             "dogs are bad", "doggy is bad too"), "dog\\b") 
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
# \\s: whitespace
str_detect(c("dog", "dog is good", 
             "dogs are bad", "doggy is bad too"), "\\s") 
## [1] FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE

Regular Expressions: Capture Groups

  • Parentheses remember the match within them to use later
str_replace(days, "([aeiou])", "\\1\\1\\1") 
## [1] "Suuunday"    "Mooonday"    "Tuuuesday"   "Weeednesday"
## [5] "Thuuursday"  "Friiiday"    "Saaaturday"
  • What will this do?
str_replace(days, "([aeiou])(.*)([aeiou])", "\\3\\2\\1")

Regular Expressions: Capture Groups

  • Parentheses remember the match within them to use later
str_replace(days, "([aeiou])", "\\1\\1\\1") 
## [1] "Suuunday"    "Mooonday"    "Tuuuesday"   "Weeednesday"
## [5] "Thuuursday"  "Friiiday"    "Saaaturday"
  • What will this do?
str_replace(days, "([aeiou])(.*)([aeiou])", "\\3\\2\\1")
## [1] "Sanduy"    "Mandoy"    "Taesduy"   "Wadnesdey"
## [5] "Tharsduy"  "Fradiy"    "Saturday"

Regular Expressions: Capture Groups

  • With greedy repetition, we match first and last vowels
str_replace(days, "([aeiou])(.*)([aeiou])", "\\3\\2\\1") 
## [1] "Sanduy"    "Mandoy"    "Taesduy"   "Wadnesdey"
## [5] "Tharsduy"  "Fradiy"    "Saturday"
  • With lazy repetition, we matches first and second vowels
str_replace(days, "([aeiou])(.*?)([aeiou])", "\\3\\2\\1")
## [1] "Sanduy"    "Mandoy"    "Teusday"   "Wednesday"
## [5] "Tharsduy"  "Fradiy"    "Sutarday"

Regular Expressions: Capture Groups

  • Capture groups can be nested: the count goes with the opening paren
monster_truck_days <- str_replace(days, "(.*(day))",
                                  "\\1\\1\\1\\2\\2\\2") 
monster_truck_days
## [1] "SundaySundaySundaydaydayday"         
## [2] "MondayMondayMondaydaydayday"         
## [3] "TuesdayTuesdayTuesdaydaydayday"      
## [4] "WednesdayWednesdayWednesdaydaydayday"
## [5] "ThursdayThursdayThursdaydaydayday"   
## [6] "FridayFridayFridaydaydayday"         
## [7] "SaturdaySaturdaySaturdaydaydayday"

Regular Expressions: Capture Groups

  • Capture groups also allow you to apply repetition, etc., to whole group
str_detect(monster_truck_days, "(day){3}")
## [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE

Regular Expressions: An Example

Regular Expressions: An Example

day_pattern <- str_c(days, collapse = "|")
weather_df <- weather %>% 
    tibble(text = .,
           day_date = if_else(str_detect(text, day_pattern),
                              text,
                              NA_character_)) %>% 
    filter(!(str_detect(text, "^\\s*$")))
weather_df
## # A tibble: 15 x 2
##    text        day_date   
##    <chr>       <chr>      
##  1 January     <NA>       
##  2 Sunday 1    Sunday 1   
##  3 Sunny       <NA>       
##  4 Monday 2    Monday 2   
##  5 Sunny       <NA>       
##  6 Tuesday 3   Tuesday 3  
##  7 Rainy       <NA>       
##  8 Wednesday 4 Wednesday 4
##  9 Rainy       <NA>       
## 10 Thursday 5  Thursday 5 
## 11 Sunny       <NA>       
## 12 Friday 6    Friday 6   
## 13 Sunny       <NA>       
## 14 Saturday 7  Saturday 7 
## 15 Rainy       <NA>

Regular Expressions: An Example

weather_df <- weather_df %>% 
    fill(day_date) %>%      # from tidyr: fills na with last observed value
    filter(text!=day_date) %>% 
    separate(day_date, into = c("day", "date"), sep = " ")
